					<h4 class="text-center">Managerial Career</h4>
          <p> <b>2000</b> :  Mourinho moved up from his role as assistant manager at Benfica to replace manager Jupp Heynckes after the fourth week of the Primeira Liga.</p>
          <p> <b>2001</b> :  Mourinho found a new managerial post with União de Leiria.</p>
          <p> <b>2002 - 2004</b> : Mourinho was then hand-picked by Porto to replace Octávio Machado on 23 January 2002 where he Recorded huge successes including winning the UEFA Champions League in the 2003 -2004 season.</p>
          <p> <b>2004 - 2008</b> : On 2 June 2004, Mourinho moved to Chelsea on a three-year contract, after a £1.7 million compensation package was agreed with Porto. Under Mourinho, Chelsea secured their first top-flight domestic title in 50 years, setting a string of English football records in the process, including the most points ever achieved in the Premier League (95) and the fewest goals conceded (15).</p>
          <p> <b>2008 - 2010</b> : On 2 June 2008, Mourinho was appointed the successor of Roberto Mancini at Internazionale on a three-year contract. Internazionale beat Roma on penalties to win the SuperCoppa Italiana, and also win the Seria A in Mourinho's first season in-charge. <br/>
	            	On 22 May 2010, Inter won the 2010 Champions League after beating Bayern Munich 2–0, and in doing so became the first Italian club to complete the treble, with Mourinho personally celebrating his second "treble win" in his managerial career and second Champions League title.</p>
          <p><b>2010-2013</b> : On 31 May 2010, Mourinho was unveiled as the new manager of Real Madrid after signing a four-year contract.<br/>
	            	On 20 April 2011, Mourinho won his first trophy in Spanish football as Real Madrid defeated arch-rivals Barcelona 1–0 in the Copa del Rey final, ending Real Madrid's 18-year-long Copa del Rey drought.<br/>
	            	On 2 May 2012, Real Madrid won 0–3 against Athletic Bilbao to clinch the Liga title for the first time in four years. <br/>
	            	</p>
          <p> <b>2013 - 2015</b> : Mourinho was appointed the manager of Chelsea for the second time on June 3, 2013. He went on to win the League Cup and the Premier League in the 2014/2015 season and was subsequently named Premier League Manager of the Season. <br/>
	            	Following a run of poor results in the 2015/2016 season, Chelsea parted company with Mourinho "by mutual consent" according to statement from the club.</p>
          <p> <b>2016 - date</b> : On 27 May 2016, Mourinho signed a three-year contract to become the next Manager of Manchester United. After winning his first trophy as United's manager by beating reigning Premier League Champions, Leicester City, in the Community Shield match; Mourinho went on to become the first United manager to win a major trophy in his first season when Manchester United beat Southamptom to lift the EFL Cup. <br/>
	            	On 24 May 2017, Manchester United won the Europa League courtesy of a 2–0 win over AFC Ajax. This was Mourinho's second major trophy of his first season as Manchester United manager. It also maintained his 100% record of winning every major European Cup final as a manager.</p>
